Often, after a Neighborhood Watch has addressed its original issue, members lose interest. It is important for leaders to remain passionate and committed for the long term. One way to accomplish this is to design new projects so that there is always a goal towards which the team of volunteers is aspiring. Arson prevention projects should focus on identifying and removing what could burn or materials that an arsonist could use to start a fire, such as:
Clean up the neighborhood by removing all garbage, material, and excess vegetation that is capable of being ignited. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/87/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove all possible sources of ignition such as flammable liquids and unused gas containers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bd/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bd/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove abandoned vehicles. According to the USFA’s NFIRS data and the NFPA, there is an annual estimated average of 25,328 intentional fires involving vehicles. Most car fires are started to cover up other criminal activity or simply as an act of vandalism. An abandoned car is a target for arson. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Secure abandoned and vacant homes which are potential arson targets. This may be comprised with additional locks or the boarding up of broken windows or other openings with plywood. Communicate with the owner that authorities are concerned about the vacant home and explain why. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Encourage the fire department to conduct frequent fire code inspections. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/62/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/62/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Contact public works to disconnect all utilities at the street. This includes natural gas, water, and electricity. If there are liquefied petroleum gas tanks, they should be disconnected and removed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-5Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Encourage Neighborhood Watch members to patrol these areas and write down descriptions, license plates of suspicious vehicles, and potential suspect descriptions. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/70/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/70/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Illuminate the exterior and entrances. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/88/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/88/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use motion-activated lighting near doors and windows. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Keep shrubbery and trees trimmed so the building can be observed by passing patrols. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/df/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If in a rural setting, ensure crops are far enough away to allow proper illumination of the area. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/aa/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/aa/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Do not allow church signs to block the view of the building. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Many buildings have basement entries that are hidden from view. These should be secured with locking, ground-level doors when the building is not in use. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Ladders, external stairways, and fire escapes allowing access to the roof should be secured. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet7.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet7.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Painting the building white or constructing it with light-colored brick makes a human figure more readily seen at night. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet8.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet8.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/00/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet8.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet8.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider fencing the areas or sides that are not readily visible to patrols or neighbors. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/64/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet9.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet9.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/64/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet9.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet9.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use properly installed deadbolt locks on all exterior doors. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/56/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/56/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Windows that can be opened should have adequate locks on them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7d/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7d/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Consider decorative or wrought iron protection for windows. (Windows used as emergency exits must still be able to be opened in an emergency.) Doors should have similar protection. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/da/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/da/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Installation of a combination burglar and fire alarm with a phone dialer should be considered. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fc/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If there is a private security firm in your area, consider a contract with them as they will check the building at unscheduled intervals. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/10/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/10/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Keep a current list of all individuals that have access to keys and change locks periodically. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6e/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-18Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Keep congregation leaders informed of potential and existing problems. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/85/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Be aware of individuals who may be disgruntled or likely to cause damage to property through arson or vandalism. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/63/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/63/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Be aware that vandalism may precede arson! {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Open avenues of communication with fire and law enforcement officials regarding the arson problem places of worship are facing. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/48/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Appoint a person from the congregation to be a liaison with law and fire officials. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Promote neighborhood watches and educate the neighbors with the lighting arrangements (motion lights, etc.). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5f/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-17Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Educate neighbors on how to recognize and report unusual activities. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet7.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet7.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet7.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet7.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Encourage neighbors to make note of strangers spending time in the neighborhood, either on foot or in vehicles. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Go-to-a-Swim-Meet-Alone-Step-1.jpg/v4-460px-Go-to-a-Swim-Meet-Alone-Step-1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Go-to-a-Swim-Meet-Alone-Step-1.jpg/v4-760px-Go-to-a-Swim-Meet-Alone-Step-1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Write down the license plate numbers of suspicious vehicles and inform the proper authorities swiftly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/70/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg/v4-460px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/70/Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg/v4-760px-Prevent-Arson-in-Your-Community-Step-19Bullet9.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
